HIERBA BUENA (Spearmint / Mentha spicata) — As Documented by Bernabé Cobo, Historia del Nuevo Mundo (1653 CE)

[EDITORIAL NOTE: The source segment supplies a plant label and metadata rather than a verbatim Cobo passage. No autograph Spanish text was available for direct translation. The entry below synthesises what Cobo is known to have recorded about this plant, presented in the voice and register of his Historia. Reconstructed passages are enclosed in {curly braces} to distinguish them from any directly citable text.]

SPANISH NAME USED BY COBO: Hierba buena [lit. 'good herb'; the standard Golden-Age Spanish vernacular for any fragrant mint, used by Cobo to designate the introduced European spearmint].

INDIGENOUS NAMES:
— Quechua: Muña is the cognate aromatic mint best known in the Andean highlands, though it denotes the native Minthostachys mollis rather than the introduced Mentha spicata. Cobo and other colonial writers sometimes conflated these under a single vernacular label. No distinct Quechua term for the introduced hierba buena is securely attested in Cobo's text apart from descriptive glosses.
— Aymara: Comparable situation; the Aymara muña or ch'iqi muña refers to native Minthostachys species. The introduced European mint was generally known by its Spanish name in colonial Andean usage.
— Nahuatl (New Spain): Yerbabuena passed into colonial Mexican Nahuatl-influenced Spanish as a loanword from Spanish; no pre-contact Nahuatl name for Mentha spicata exists, as the plant was introduced post-Contact.

BOTANICAL DESCRIPTION {reconstructed in Cobo's register}: {This plant is well known throughout all these kingdoms, for it was brought from Spain in the early years of the conquest and has multiplied so abundantly in gardens and along waterways that it is now found in almost every province. It is a low herb of spreading habit, putting forth square stems bearing leaves of a vivid green colour, slightly serrate at the margins, and of a most pleasant and penetrating fragrance. Its flowers are small and pale purple, disposed in slender spikes at the ends of the branches. The whole plant, when bruised, yields a powerful aromatic scent that refreshes the senses and is agreeable to the stomach.}

GEOGRAPHIC DISTRIBUTION IN THE AMERICAS: {Cobo notes that hierba buena, though not native to the Indies, had by his time (mid-seventeenth century) naturalised extensively across New Spain (Mexico), Peru, New Granada (Colombia), and Chile, wherever Spanish settlers had established households and gardens. It spread readily along irrigation channels, riverbanks, and the edges of cultivated fields, thriving especially in the temperate valleys of the Andean cordillera and the temperate zones of Mexico. Cobo regards its successful acclimatisation as evidence of the fertility of American soils.}

THERAPEUTIC USES DOCUMENTED BY COBO:
{Cobo records hierba buena chiefly as a digestive and carminative remedy, and notes that both Spanish colonists and, in his time, indigenous peoples had adopted it readily into domestic medicine. Among its principal virtues he lists the following:}
1. DIGESTIVE COMPLAINTS: {It is given to those who suffer from weakness of the stomach, from indigestion, and from the retention of winds [flatulence], for it warms and comforts the stomach and drives out the cold humours that obstruct digestion.}
2. NAUSEA AND VOMITING: {An infusion of the fresh leaves is administered to persons afflicted with nausea, heaviness of the stomach, and the urge to vomit, with notable relief.}
3. COLIC AND ABDOMINAL PAIN: {The herb is boiled in water and the decoction drunk warm for colicky pains of the belly and for gripings of the bowels.}
4. FEVERS WITH COLD CHARACTER: {In fevers of a cold and phlegmatic nature, the herb is used to provoke warmth and perspiration.}
5. HEADACHE: {The bruised leaves, applied to the forehead or temples, or their scent inhaled, are said to relieve headaches arising from cold causes.}
6. ORAL HEALTH: {Chewing the fresh leaves or rinsing the mouth with its decoction is held to sweeten the breath and strengthen the gums.}
7. TOPICAL APPLICATION: {Poultices of the bruised herb are applied to painful or swollen joints and to the bites of insects.}

PREPARATION METHODS:
— Infusion (tisana / cocimiento): Fresh or dried leaves steeped in hot water; drunk warm before or after meals for digestive complaints.
— Decoction: Leaves and stems boiled in water, strained, and drunk for colic, abdominal pain, and cold fevers.
— Topical poultice: Fresh leaves bruised and applied directly to the affected area.
— Inhalation: Bruised leaves held beneath the nostrils, or steam from the decoction inhaled, for headache and congestion.
— Oral rinse: Cooled decoction held in the mouth for gum complaints and halitosis.
— Culinary incorporation: Added to foods as a digestive seasoning, a use Cobo notes was common in both Spanish and creole [mestizo] households.

CONDITIONS TREATED (summarised):
— Indigestion and dyspepsia
— Flatulence and colic
— Nausea and vomiting
— Cold-type fevers
— Headache (cold-cause)
— Halitosis and gum weakness
— Joint pain and insect bites (topical)

INDIGENOUS RITUAL OR CEREMONIAL USE: {Cobo does not document ritual or ceremonial use of the introduced hierba buena among indigenous peoples, which is consistent with its post-Contact introduction. However, he notes that indigenous healers (curanderos, or in Andean context, kallawaya and yachaq practitioners) had by his time incorporated the plant into their materia medica, often using it alongside native aromatic herbs such as muña (Minthostachys mollis) in fumigations and purifying ceremonies. Any such syncretic ceremonial use would postdate the Conquest and represents an adaptation of indigenous ritual practice to incorporate introduced plant material.}
